GANs

GANs refers to Generative Adversarial Networks.

  • 2 networks (Generator & Discriminator) plays Min-Max game and aims to reach to Nash equilibrium.
  • GANs are generative models. 2 nets learn each other, especially, Generator uses the signal (loss) from the Discriminator (classifier) to approximate his intractable cost function.

Manifold Assumption

The data distribution lie close to a low-dimensional manifold Example: consider image data

  • Very high dimensional (1,000,000D)
  • A randomly generated image will almost certainly not look like any real world scene
  • The space of images that occur in nature is almost completely empty
  • Hypothesis: real world images lie on a smooth, low-dimensional manifold
  • Manifold distance is a good measure of similarity

Assumption: Support of lie on low dimensional manifolds

  • we now assume Support of lives in a low-dimensional manifold embedded in a higher-dimensional space (input space)
  • now think about what does the generator net do?
    • we first randomly generate z and dim(z) << dim(x)
    • we use G(z) as a non-linear mapping from dim(z) to dim(x)
    • so what does the p_g represent eventually?
    • since Manifold learning is an approach to non-linear dimensionality reduction
    • p_g represents a consequence after reverting manifold learning
  • we now assume Support of lie on low dimensional manifolds
    • this means each one of manifold hardly fills up the whole high dimensional space
    • they are almost certainly gonna be disjoint, the case where they overlap is neglectable

manifold assumption with perfect D* and JS divergence

  • since they can not fills up the whole input space, there always exists a D* that separates real and fake samples 100% correctly. they are almost disjoint, this is where cause Gradient vanishing ,from experiment result, it shows loss term eventually is 0. ()

WGANs

  • GAN
    • As a result, training a GAN faces a dilemma:
    • If the discriminator behaves badly, the generator does not have accurate feedback and the loss function cannot represent the reality.
    • If the discriminator does a great job, the gradient of the loss function drops down to close to zero and the learning becomes super slow or even jammed.
    • JS divergence is not a good metric
    • Mode collapse and unstable gradient update
  • Purpose a meaningful metric namely, Earth-Mover (EM) distance or Wasserstein-1
    • smooth and differentiable when 2 supports are disjoint
    • meaningful indicator during the training
    • stability is improved

Earth-Mover (EM) / Wasserstein Distance

is a measure of the distance between two probability distributions. informally it can be interpreted as moving piles of dirt that follow one probability distribution at a minimum cost to follow the other distribution. The cost is quantified by the amount of dirt moved times the moving distance.

  • : set of all possible joint probability distributions between Pr and Pg
  • : one transport plan .
  • : states states the percentage of dirt should be transported from point x to y.
